The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Friday, February 20, 2004 				 Naxalites call for Bihar bandh
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Patna, Feb. 19: The Peoples War and the Maoist Communist Centre have called a statewide bandh on February 27 in protest against the alleged systematic repression unleashed on their cadre and supporters by the Union government.																								A joint communiqu issued by the two banned rebel outfits said the repression tactic, based on the Andhra model, was being adopted in nine states, including Bihar and Jharkhand. The other states, it added, were Bengal, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh and Maharashtra.																								The joint operational command constituted by the Centre, which comprises personnel from (the) armed forces, paramilitary forces and other police establishments, is aimed at crushing all peoples movements, including revolutionary peasant struggles. The Centre has already announced to bear the cost of this onslaught. We will oppose this everywhere, the release said.																								The outfits have exempted health services, newspaper establishments, water and milk supply and fire services from the call.																								But they have appealed to all shopkeepers, traders, rail and road transport employees, vehicle owners and government employees to make the bandh successful.
